sentences: Pauline Huguette Dreyfus (30 November 1928 – 16 May 2016) was a French harpsichordist.
Dreyfus was born in Mulhouse, Alsace, France, on 30 November 1928 to Fernand and Marguerite Dreyfus.
In December 1942, she, her brother, and her father escaped into Switzerland and settled in Geneva where they had relatives.
In 1946, she began working with renowned piano teacher Lazare Lévy.

In 1950, having learned that music historian Norbert Dufourcq was to give special classes on the music of Johann Sebastian Bach (in recognition of the bicentennial of Bach's death) at the Conservatoire de Paris, she entered into the class and remained there for four years.

In 1958, Dreyfus won the Geneva international harpsichord competition, becoming a prominent figure of ancient Renaissance and Baroque music and of the revival of the harpsichord in France.
